The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Wednesday, April 28, 2004  Business Briefs																								 New Delhi, April 27: The minimum capital required for setting up a pension fund is likely to be fixed at Rs 25 crore, one fourth of what is prescribed for the insurers. This minimum capital requirement has been mooted by India Invest Economic Foundation, adviser to the government on pension, which recently submitted broad contours for the operational framework and selection of pension fund managers in the light of the recent opening up of the sector. 																								 New Delhi, April 27: IFCIs merger with Punjab National Bank may be delayed till October. PNB, which has engaged SBI Caps for assessing the cost of acquiring IFCI, is expected to get a report in June, official sources said.																								 New Delhi, April 27: Royal Dutch/Shell has formally applied for a licence to sell petrol and diesel in India saying it has completed the pre-requisite investment of Rs 2,000 crore in oil infrastructure in the country.																								 New Delhi, April 27: Small Industries Development Bank of India (Sidbi) will soon start investing in equity of small companies for which the size of its venture-capital fund will be enhanced five-fold to Rs 500 crore.																								 Mumbai, April 27: Great Eastern Shipping Company Ltd (Gesco) has decided to opt for early redemption of its 10.5 per cent cumulative redeemable non-convertible preference shares.
